<TITLE> China's growing luxury market </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, 21 Jan (bdnews24.com/Reuters)--- A new report says China is on track to become the world's biggest market for luxury goods within five to seven years As Chinese wealth grows, the nation is set to become the world's top luxury goods market within seven years, a new report suggests. The report by the Boston Consulting Group says the world's current No. 3 economy offers great hope for high-end companies. The company's Vincent Liu says luxury brands have performed surprisingly well in China. (SOUNDBITE) (English) PRINCIPAL AT THE BOSTON CONSULTING GROUP VINCENT LIU SAYING: "China remains the bright spark for many of the luxury companies. Even in 2009, consumers remained quite optimistic relative to many of the developed countries' consumers, and many companies, many luxury companies, actually announced a very positive result, even for 2009." China said Thursday its economy grew 8.7 percent in 2009, thanks in part to a huge stimulus package rolled out to counter the global financial crisis. Officially-Communist, the nation is a relatively new luxury market with consumers looking for signs of their new-found wealth. (SOUNDBITE) (English) PRINCIPAL AT THE BOSTON CONSULTING GROUP VINCENT LIU SAYING: "Right now, Chinese consumers are relatively younger than most of the clients luxury companies have in other places - most of them are in the 25 to 35 age span. And second is the mobility, meaning many people have increasing income so, you know, yesterday they couldn't afford the luxury products, but one, two, three years down the road, they will have a means to afford and the interest and demand for that product." Currently over 50 percent of Chinese luxury purchases are overseas or in Hong Kong and Macau, where taxes are below the mainl
